@startuml
title Stack frame, the overflow, and the three mitigations

skinparam shadowing false
skinparam rectangle {
  BackgroundColor #f5f5f5
}

rectangle "Higher addresses" as hi
rectangle "RET\n(saved return address)" as ret #ffd0d0
rectangle "saved RBP\n(frame pointer)" as rbp
rectangle "stack canary\n(random guard value)" as canary #d0ffd0
rectangle "char buf[64]\n(local buffer)" as buf
rectangle "Lower addresses" as lo

hi -down-> ret
ret -down-> rbp
rbp -down-> canary
canary -down-> buf
buf -down-> lo

note right of buf
  strcpy(buf, argv[1]) copies without a bound.
  Writes grow UPWARD toward saved RBP and RET,
  so an over-long argv[1] overwrites the return
  address and redirects control flow on return.
end note

note right of canary
  CANARY: a random value placed before RET; checked
  on return. An overflow that reaches RET also
  corrupts it, so the mismatch aborts the program.
end note

note right of ret
  NX: mark the stack non-executable, so injected
  shellcode in buf cannot run (MULTICS idea).
  ASLR: randomize segment base addresses, so the
  attacker cannot predict where to jump.
end note
@enduml
